# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gamemaker-studio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:gamemaker-studio/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:gamemaker-studio/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GameMaker accommodates the creation of cross-platform and multi-genre video games using a custom drag-and-drop visual programming language or a scripting language known as Game Maker Language (GML), which can be used to develop more advanced games.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GameMaker was originally designed to allow novice programmers to be able to make computer games without much programming knowledge by use of these actions.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Recent versions of software also focus on appealing to advanced developers.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GameMaker is primarily intended for making games with 2D graphics, allowing out-of-box use of raster graphics, vector graphics (via SWF), and 2D skeletal animations (via Esoteric Software's Spine) along with a large standard library for drawing graphics and 2D primitives.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] While the software allows for limited use of 3D graphics, this is in the form of vertex buffer and matrix functions, and as such not intended for novice users.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] The engine uses Direct3D on Windows, UWP, and Xbox One; OpenGL on macOS and Linux; OpenGL ES on Android and iOS, WebGL or 2d canvas on HTML5, and proprietary APIs on consoles.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] The engine's primary element is an IDE with built-in editors for raster graphics, level design, scripting, paths, and shaders (GLSL or HLSL).
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Additional functionality can be implemented in software's scripting language or platform-specific native extensions.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] In GameMaker Studio 2, users can choose whether to export the game as an NSIS installer, or a .zip file containing the game, the data.win file, and any files added under the "Included Files" tab in the editor.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] In past, GameMaker supported building for Windows Phone (deprecated in favor of UWP), Tizen, PlayStation 3, and PlayStation Vita (not supported in GMS2 "largely for business reasons").
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] PlayStation Portable support was demonstrated in May 2010, but never made publicly available (with only a small selection of titles using it).
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Between 2007 and 2011, YoYo Games maintained a custom web player plugin for GameMaker games before releasing it as open-source mid-2011 and eventually deprecating it in favor of HTML5 export.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Prior to August 2021, users had to obtain a single-purchase license for one of five different platforms, excluding consoles, depending on the target platform they wanted to publish on (such as desktop or mobile).
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] An annual license was required to publish for consoles, which was also contained in an all-encompassing annual Ultimate license that covered all supported platforms.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Yoyo Games announced a change to the licensing approach in August 2021, allowing GameMaker to be used for free to learn, and eliminating the single-purchase options.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Instead, it simplified the license scheme to only two tiers, one that supported publishing on all non-console platforms, and a higher tier that added in console platform publishing support at a lower rate than the prior Ultimate license.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] These changes were aided by the financial investment of Opera into YoYo Games to help reduce costs for GameMaker users.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] On 22 November 2023, GameMaker announced that it would be "free for non-commercial use on all platforms (excluding console)," and the current subscription system would be replaced by a one-time license.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GameMaker Language (GML) is GameMaker's scripting language.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] It is an imperative, dynamically typed language commonly likened to JavaScript and C-like languages.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] The language's default mode of operation on native platforms is via a stack machine; it can also be source-to-source compiled to C++ via LLVM for higher performance.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] On HTML5, GML is source-to-source compiled to JavaScript with optimizations and minification applied in non-debug builds.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GML Visual (originally called "Drag and Drop") is GameMaker's visual scripting tool.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GML Visual allows developers to perform common tasks (like instantiating objects, calling functions, or working with files and data structures) without having to write a single line of code.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GameMaker was originally developed by Mark Overmars.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] The program was first released on 15 November 1999 under the name of Animo (at the time, it was just a graphics tool with limited visual scripting capabilities).
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] The first versions of the program were being developed in Delphi.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Subsequent releases saw the name changed to Game Maker and software moving towards more general-purpose 2D game development.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Versions 5.0 and below were freeware; version 5.1 introduced an optional registration fee; version 5.3 (January 2004) introduced a number of new features for registered users, including particle systems, networking, and possibility to extend games using DLLs.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Version 6.0 (October 2004) introduced limited functionality for use of 3D graphics, as well as migrating the runtime's drawing pipeline from VCL to DirectX.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Growing public interest led Overmars to seek help in expanding the program, which led to partnership with YoYo Games in 2007.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] From this point onward, development was handled by YoYo Games while Overmars retained a position as one of the company's directors.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Version 7.0 was the first to emerge under this partnership.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] The first macOS compatible version of the program was released in 2009, allowing games to be made for two operating systems with minimal changes.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Version 8.1 (April 2011) saw the name changed to GameMaker (lacking a space) to avoid any confusion with the 1991 software *Game-Maker*.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] September 2011 saw the initial release of "GameMaker: HTML5" - a new version of software with capability to export games for web browsers along with desktop.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GameMaker: Studio entered public beta in March 2012 and enjoyed a full release in May 2012.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] This version also had the runtime rewritten in C++ to address performance concerns with previous versions.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Initial supported platforms included Windows, Mac, HTML5, Android, and iOS.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Additional platforms and features were introduced over the years following; Late 2012 there was an accident with anti-piracy measures misfiring for some legitimate users.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] In February 2015, GameMaker was acquired by Playtech together with YoYo Games.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Announcement reassured that GameMaker will be further improved and states plans to appeal to broader demographic, including more advanced developers.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] November 2016 saw the initial release of GameMaker Studio 2 beta, with full release in March 2017.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] This version sports a completely redesigned IDE (rewritten in C#) and a number of new editor and runtime features.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] In August 2020, major update 2.3 was released, bringing a host of new features to IDE, runtime, and the scripting language.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] In January 2021, YoYo Games was sold to Opera Software for roughly 10 million USD.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] The development team of GameMaker remains the same, and has not caused any major development changes to GameMaker Studio.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] In August 2021, YoYo Games announced that they would be changing their licenses to offer a free version of the GameMaker engine.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] In January 2022, YoYo Games changed GameMaker Studio 2's numbering scheme so the version corresponds to the year and the month it was released (For example, 2022.1 for January 2022).
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] In April 2022, YoYo Games dropped the *GameMaker Studio 2* name in order to match its new version numbering scheme, changing it to simply GameMaker.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] GameMaker was used in schools because of its drag and drop programming interface.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] It preceded programming environments which were developed for educational use such as Scratch and Walter Bender's Turtle Blocks.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] Its use in schools was preceded by Logo but Logo was text based rather than drag and drop.
[src:gamemaker-studio/gamemaker-language] For teachers using GameMaker, it shared a Constructionist learning theory with Logo.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, a **sprite** is a two-dimensional bitmap that is integrated into a larger scene, most often in a 2D video game.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Originally, the term *sprite* referred to fixed-sized objects composited together, by hardware, with a background.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Use of the term has since become more general.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware varies in the number of sprites supported, the size and colors of each sprite, and special effects such as scaling or reporting pixel-precise overlap.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware composition of sprites occurs as each scan line is prepared for the video output device, such as a cathode-ray tube, without involvement of the main CPU and without the need for a full-screen frame buffer.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites can be positioned or altered by setting attributes used during the hardware composition process.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The number of sprites which can be displayed per scan line is often lower than the total number of sprites a system supports.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] For example, the Texas Instruments TMS9918 chip supports 32 sprites, but only four can appear on the same scan line.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The CPUs in modern computers, video game consoles, and mobile devices are fast enough that bitmaps can be drawn into a frame buffer without special hardware assistance.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Beyond that, GPUs can render vast numbers of scaled, rotated, anti-aliased, partially translucent, very high resolution images in parallel with the CPU.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Karl Guttag, one of two engineers for the 1979 Texas Instruments TMS9918 video display processor, this use of the word *sprite* came from David Ackley, a manager at TI.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] It was also used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The term was derived from the fact that sprites "float" on top of the background image without overwriting it, much like a ghost or mythological sprite.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The use of sprites originated with arcade video games.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Nolan Bushnell came up with the original concept when he developed the first arcade video game, *Computer Space* (1971).
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Technical limitations made it difficult to adapt the early mainframe game *Spacewar!* (1962), which performed an entire screen refresh for every little movement, so he came up with a solution to the problem: controlling each individual game element with a dedicated transistor.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The rockets were essentially hardwired bitmaps that moved around the screen independently of the background, an important innovation for producing screen images more efficiently and providing the basis for sprite graphics.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The earliest video games to represent player characters as human player sprites were arcade sports video games, beginning with Taito's *TV Basketball*, released in April 1974 and licensed to Midway Manufacturing for release in North America.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Designed by Tomohiro Nishikado, he wanted to move beyond simple *Pong*-style rectangles to character graphics, by rearranging the rectangle shapes into objects that look like basketball players and basketball hoops.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Ramtek released another sports video game in October 1974, *Baseball*, which similarly displayed human-like characters.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The Namco Galaxian arcade system board, for the 1979 arcade game *Galaxian*, displays animated, multi-colored sprites over a scrolling background.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] It became the basis for Nintendo's *Radar Scope* and *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware and home consoles such as the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Steve Golson from General Computer Corporation, the term "stamp" was used instead of "sprite" at the time.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Signetics devised the first chips capable of generating sprite graphics (referred to as *objects* by Signetics) for home systems.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The Signetics 2636 video processors were first used in the 1978 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System and later in the 1979 Elektor TV Games Computer.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The Atari VCS, released in 1977, has a hardware sprite implementation where five graphical objects can be moved independently of the game playfield.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The term *sprite* was not in use at the time.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The VCS's sprites are called *movable objects* in the programming manual, further identified as two *players*, two *missiles*, and one *ball*.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] These each consist of a single row of pixels that are displayed on a scan line.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] To produce a two-dimensional shape, the sprite's single-row bitmap is altered by software from one scan line to the next.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The 1979 Atari 400 and 800 home computers have similar, but more elaborate, circuitry capable of moving eight single-color objects per scan line: four 8-bit wide *players* and four 2-bit wide *missiles*.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Each is the full height of the display—a long, thin strip.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] DMA from a table in memory automatically sets the graphics pattern registers for each scan line.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware registers control the horizontal position of each player and missile.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Vertical motion is achieved by moving the bitmap data within a player or missile's strip.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] The feature was called *player/missile graphics* by Atari.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Texas Instruments developed the TMS9918 chip with sprite support for its 1979 TI-99/4 home computer.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] An updated version is used in the 1981 TI-99/4A.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remained popular with the rise of 2.5D games (those which recreate a 3D game space from a 2D map) in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] A technique called billboarding allows 2.5D games to keep onscreen sprites rotated toward the player view at all times.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Some 2.5D games, such as 1993's *Doom*, allow the same entity to be represented by different sprites depending on its rotation relative to the viewer, furthering the illusion of 3D.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Fully 3D games usually present world objects as 3D models, but sprites are supported in some 3D game engines, such as GoldSrc and Unreal, and may be billboarded or locked to fixed orientations.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remain useful for small details, particle effects, and other applications where the lack of a third dimension is not a major detriment.
[src:gamemaker-studio/sprite-computer-graphics] These are base hardware specs and do not include additional programming techniques, such as using raster interrupts to repurpose sprites mid-frame.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] YoYo Games was founded in 2007 by Michel Cassius, Sandy Duncan, Spencer Hyman and James North-Hearn, former entertainment and video game industry executives.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] Duncan was appointed chief executive officer of the company.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] On 26 January 2007, Mark Overmars announced his partnership with a company based in Dundee, Scotland, called YoYo Games.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] The company established its European office in Dundee in May 2010 by opening an office within Abertay University with two team members.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] The company currently employs more than 25 employees.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] YoYo Games has announced plans to create an additional 25 positions, over the next 18 months, in systems development, software engineering, sales and customer service.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] The employees will be hired to help the company keep pace with the rapid evolution of the global games market and demand for Game Maker: Studio.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] To accommodate this expansion, in June 2013, YoYo Games moved from its old location within Abertay University into new office space on Dundee’s Waterfront redevelopment.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] On 16 February 2015 it was announced that Playtech acquired YoYo Games for £10.65 million (USD$16.4 million).
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] Shortly thereafter, Duncan stepped down from his position.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] He was later replaced by James Cox as general manager, who himself stepped down in October 2018 to be replaced by Stuart Poole in January 2019.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] Playtech sold YoYo Games to Opera for US$10 million in January 2021.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] Opera announced with YoYo's acquisition, it was launching a new Opera Gaming division alongside their browser software.
[src:gamemaker-studio/yoyo-games] In February 2021, Stuart Poole left the role of General Manager and Russell Kay was named Senior Product Director (Head of GameMaker).
